segments.text: Okay, Mr. Irvin, would you tell us your full name, the date and place of your birth?
My name is Barlow Irvin.
I was born in Cotulla, Texas on December 31, 1903.
And could you tell us a little bit about your early boyhood there in Cotulla and possibly about your elementary education on up through high school?
Well, we lived on the Irvin Ranch up until about 1909.
And then we moved to Cotulla, Texas where I spent two years and entered Cotulla public schools at the age of seven.
At that time I contacted typhoid fever and remained in Cotulla for about three months while the rest of my family moved on to San Antonio where I spent most of my early boroughhood days.
And can you remember anything about your education there?
In San Antonio?
Yeah, in San Antonio.
Well, we moved to 2001 Main Avenue, which was right across the street from the Travis Elementary School.
And I entered there after arriving in San Antonio and started my elementary education at Travis School.
I might say at this time that all my sisters went through there and also
two of my sons.
How many brothers and sisters did you have?
I had three sisters, no brothers.
No brothers.
I see.
And you have how many children now?
I have two sons, one named John Jordan, named after my father, and the other named Barlow Jr.
They both live in Dallas.
One's in the insurance business and one is an attorney.
Could you tell us your mother's name?
My mother's name was Edna Barlow Irving.
Edna Barlow, and she was born in De Niro, Texas in January, I mean July the 7th, 1875.
You know your father's birthday.
My father was John Jordan Irving.
He was born July the 4th, 1872 in Sagin, Texas.
I see.
Now, after-
You went to elementary school then.
Did you go on into high school?

Yes, after that was done, I left Travis School and went to what they called Old Main Avenue High School, which was situated about a mile and a half from my home toward the city, central part of the city.
At those days, they didn't have but one high school.
That was Old Main Avenue High School.
But in 1918, they built
another high school called Brackenridge High School, which was situated on the south side of the city.
Do you remember anything from your high school experiences?
Yes, and when I went to high school I remember, of course, at an early age I took part in athletics, and when I entered high school I was just fourteen and a half years old.
I remember the first football team I played on.
I was a freshman at the Old Main Avenue, and that was during the war, 1917 and 1918.
And, of course, we didn't have any place to practice.
We went to Brackman Park to do our practicing.
And what I remember about that particular year was that it was during the war, and we had a coach whose name was Mr. Vinnie.
B-E-N-N-E, Benny, who was an old Haskell Indian coach at that time.
And he was in the service, in the armed services and situated at Camp Travis in San Antonio.
He wasn't officially, well he wasn't an army man, but he was connected with the
In the second year, I played basketball, football, and baseball there.
In the second and third year, we always had different coaches.
The best team we had there was 1922 when we went to the state quarterfinals.
This is in football?
In football.
Could you tell us a little bit about football, high school football in those days?
Well, in San Antonio at that time, there was only one high school, two high schools later after 1918, 1919, 1920, and 21.
And we had what they called the Academic League, which involved the two high schools, San Antonio Academy, West Texas Military Academy, and Peacock Military Academy.
And besides playing what was called the Academic League,
And then later on, then we played smaller schools around that area in San Antonio.
Football in those days was a practice.
The last coach I had was a man named Spitz Clark, who was a University of Texas coach and played with the famed 2nd Texas Infantry.
Probably not many people remember that team, but it was during the war at that time and
amassed a very, very great record in army football and service football at that time.
And they had mostly the players were from the Texas schools and they had four or five outstanding ones from Texas A&M.
I see.
Then after you graduated from high school, then did you go on directly to A&M?
Yes, after I graduated from high school, I came to A&M here in the fall of 1922.
Why did you come to A&M?
Why here?
Well, because of two or three reasons.
One, because I had a ranching background.
All my forefathers and fathers and grandparents were ranch people.
And secondly, I had friends that were coming here.
And thirdly, I was interested in some form of agriculture, which I didn't ever pursue.
Did you have any thoughts then of playing football when you came here?
Yes, that was one of the reasons I came here.
At that time, Mr. Bible was coach, and I was very much involved in athletics and in football at that time, and I came here.
You see, at that time A&M had just beaten Center College, as you probably know, and they were a nationally known team, and I wanted to come to A&M because of Mr. Bible.
He was the head coach here at that time, and the fact that A&M had made a wonderful record up to
1922, you see.
And I had visions of playing and making my letter here, besides going to school.
Okay, when you started, what were some of your first impressions when you arrived in 1922 of the university?
Well, Helen, at that time the only way you could come to A&M was by train.
The Missouri Pacific and Southern
came here by train from San Antonio and we used to get off at Milano Junction and switched and came down and picked the train that came out of Fort Worth down here.
And it was, we got off at the old station which has been torn down at the west end of the campus right across, the old tracks are still there.
A&M was a school for me because of the traditions and the heritage that they had.
At that time there were a number of people from the high school that I attended that came here too.
Do you remember how your first days and weeks here, how it impressed you?
What experiences you had as a freshman?
Well, I came here.
And one reason I got in that was because the first sergeant was Fred Jagie.
He was a teacher here in the veterinarian, in the veterinarian department now.
Coach retired.
And I knew him quite well because I played football with him in high school.
and I happened to be his room orderly my freshman year, and I lived next door to him.
But A&M at that time was purely military, because I never did acquire any, never did go over high military because I wasn't interested in it very much.
The only thing they had in those days was what they called the casuals, they were people
I forgot the names of those two dormitories they had there, but Military Walker and everything was military at that time.
And during my freshman year, of course, it was pretty, the hazing was pretty severe.
The fact of the business, the more they haze you, the better they liked you.
Oh, my.
Of course at that time they had what they called the Junior Banquet.
Are you familiar with that?
The old Junior Banquet?
No sir, I'm not.
Well that was when the president had this Junior Banquet and they had a whole week of it.
They tried to get the headmaster of the Junior Banquet or the president of it, or he would
be disguised and they would try to catch him, you see, before he went into this banquet on a certain particular day.
And of course, everybody was involved in it, including the freshmen.
And it was, they finally did away with the junior banquet because it was really gotten out of hand and the people in the authorities finally did away with it.
But A&M at that time was just, it was,
I wouldn't call it a cow college, but it was a great institution.
And most of the times, the military end of it, and plus the educational end of it, had grown immensely.
And it was a, you look back, A&M today is not the A&M of the 20s.
We all know that.
Well, did you start playing football your freshman year?
Yes, I played football under Colonel Frank Anderson.
Colonel Frank Anderson.
He still lives here, and he was a track coach.
Oh, I see.
What was this then, a freshman team?
A freshman team.
You see, back in those days, they had a freshman team.
And what I'm reminded about the freshman team was that after we had won, A&M had gotten
All this publicity, or you might say national recognition on account of beating Santa College.
And on that team, we had about 18, I think about 15 to 18 high school captains that came here to be a member of the freshman team.
And we had a good season.
We played six or seven games and didn't lose but won.
I think that was Sam Houston College at that time.
Can you remember some of the other opponents you played?
I played the Port Arthur Pirates, that was the semi-pro team at Port Arthur.
Mm-hmm.
San Houston State Teachers, St. Edward's, Allen Academy.
I don't know, I played five games.
Mm-hmm.
And then when you moved into your sophomore year, did you then move up to the varsity then?
Yes, I moved up to the varsity.
See, in those days, Mr. Bible was the owner.
He was the head coach, and we had a line coach.
We didn't have many coaches.
And he didn't give many letters.
See, all the three years that I lettered in football, he didn't give over 15 varsity letters.
And so it was pretty tough to make.
My sophomore year, there weren't but three of us that lettered that year, and one was Norman Dansby, who lived in Bryan, and one was Mule Wilson, who later played professional football.
And myself was only three sophomores that lettered that year.
What were the requirements for lettering at that time?
Do you remember?
Was it a personal thing?
Well, yes, it was.
You had towe really didn't have anywell, it did, too.
I have the rules out there in the university now.
We have the rules that were set up.
But during the 20s, I don't think we had any exact rules.
You had to play so many minutes.
It finally went into that you had to play so many minutes.
And I know my year that I lettered, my sophomore year, because I played most of the Rice game after Bull Johnson, who was supposed to have been one of the All-Southwest Conference guards.
beat a seven to nothing.
That was the first defeat they had by a conference team in 1923.
And then it went on in 24 and we had a very fairly good team that year.
The records indicate I think we had about a seventh, had a six for four record.
But most of these players that
In 1924, we were defeated in Austin by a score of seven to nothing.
And that was beginningthat's when the Memorial Stadium was dedicated, actually.
That was the first year, 1924.
It was also the beginning of the Memorial Stadium jinx.
Yeah, that's right.
And it was a peculiar game.
The game seesawed back and forth.
We had a little boy named Bob Berry threw a pass and it deflected.
No, Texas threw a pass and our defensive man deflected the ball and it went into the arms of one of the Texas players and he ran for touchdown and that was all of it.
Seven to nothing.
In those days the scores weren't very high.
Did you play both ways then?
Yes, we played both ways.
We didn't have any offense and defense.
In fact, you had to be in pretty fair shape.
Of course, your opponent had to be in good shape too because you made substitutions.
They weren't substituted as a whole team.
Individually, they were substituted mostly.
The Southwest Conference has grown tremendously.
In those days, A&M and Texas, either one of them won the conference, up until Baylor and SMU got into the picture.
And that's when Ray Morrison started his, Ray Morrison was the coach at SMU when he had his good teams in 23, and I forgot the other one, he won the Southwest Conference.
And then Frank Bridges came along at Baylor.
and won the conference in 22 and 24, I believe.
That's to my recollection, to show it in there.
But they got into, they were tired of A&M and Texas dominating the athletic scene, so they got into this, what we call now, proselytizing.
I don't wanna.
Is this maybe the beginning of the heavy recruiting?
Yes.
And I hate to say this, but it's the starting of it.
You see, during those days, everybody paid their own way.
See, it was an honor to win your varsity letter, but the boys that played football in those days, we didn't have anything such as scholarship.
That was unknown in those days.

I might say that SMU and Baylor and some of these other schools, in order to keep step with the other two state schools, they started giving scholarships, which enticed the players to their institution.
I see.
Now at this time, when you were playing football at A&M, did you live with the other members of the cadet corps?
Oh, yes.
Do you think this was a good thing?
Yes, I do.
Except during the football season, and I haven't got up to the 25 team yet, but we would live in what they call the postgraduate hall, which is located, was located by where the old hospital was.
They call it the graduate hall.
A lot of the professionals lived there.
And during the season, we would move over there for three months and then move back there
I'm saying for the players to live with it.
Don't you think maybe it kept you closer to the rest of the student body?
Yes, it would have because I know in my case, I got to know the roommates and then also the people in my dormitory after the season was over, I became just one of them.
And they were more interested in me.
there, fellow?
It's probably too bad.
I doubt if it would work anymore today, but it's an interesting idea.
Well, see it's like everything else, it's grown out of proportion and I doubt very seriously whether it would work now.
You see, as we get to this new dormitory we have here, things are just out of proportion.
It's not like it used to
Yes, I suppose.
That's progress, you see.
Now, would you tell us about the 25 team?
Well, up to 25, you see, we hadn't had a good team in 23 and 24.
And this 25 team was mostly, a good many of them were the boys that came here as freshmen.
We played together.
And the 25 team, we weren't a very outstanding team, but we were good enough to win the Southwest Conference, which we hadn't won since back in
Neil Wilson, who was a great punter and a great football player, and a little boy by the name of Bob Berry.
He wasn't over five feet five.
And the other one, we had a Japanese named Taro Kishi who played a lot.
He was a Japanese boy.
And he played one halfback, and Wilson the other, and we had a little boy named McGuire playing fullback.
Barry.
But what made that team finally gel was the fact that Keisha got hurt right before we played Baylor.
And into the lineup came Joel Hunt, who you've known about.
As goes the saying, be in the right place at the right time.
Up to that time, Joel was unknown because he had been in Waco High School and he was sort of understudied to, I forgot the name of that, Booty Johnson up there.
But we were playing Baylor at that time, and up to that part of the season, we hadn't been defeated.
But Kisha got hurt, and they inserted Joel in there, and he just ran wild.
He scored two touchdowns on pretty good-sized runs, which we didn't have that then.
We won the game 14-7.
From then on, we gained momentum, and we continued on and won the rest of our games.
except for TCU in which there was a high wind blowing and they beat us three to nothing on the field goal.
But we came back and defeated Rice and then defeated Texas 28 to nothing, the biggest score that's ever been run up against Texas in the history of A&M and Texas series.
So we won the conference
Did you play any bowl games, any bowl games that year?
No, the bowl game was not, they hadn't come into existence at that time.
There were a few around occasionally, weren't they?
Yeah.
But they weren't every year.
See the Cotton Bowl didn't, bowls didn't start until the thirties, thirties.
I think T.C.
and Marquette played the first bowl game.
What do you think was your best game?
Oh, I don't know.
You must have one game you felt that stood out, that you felt you played your best in.
Well, I guess I wasn't, I was just good in the state, but I wasn't an outstanding football player.
I mean, I guess that the best game I played was when I was a sophomore against Texas.
Hm.
They put me into the lineup when they had the ball on the one yard line.
Mm-hm.
mind stood out that way.
I would think so.
Especially if they ran at your position each time.
Well now after you graduated, what did you do?
Well I went back to San Antonio and then this fella named Jim Kendricks who was quite a character.
He had been playing professional football up in New York in the east for about 10 years
And so he had been given the position as the coach and manager of the Buffalo Bisons, who was a member of the National Professional Football Team.
And he gathered up a bunch of A&M, three A&M players, myself, Neil Wilson, and Neely Allison, and we had about five from Oklahoma and one from Trinity.
And we didn't, I don't think we had a Texas boy, and we had four from Baylor that had played in 1922.
Top Weathers, and Wesley Bradshaw, and Riley Biggs, and another one I'll think of in a minute.
And we didn't have the 16 or 17 players.
But the unique thing about this whole deal was that we traveled in Model D cars.
Had to start out in advance, didn't you?
Yeah, and so this fellow, he was a character in himself.
We started out and we had four Model Ts.
We started from Texas and those Model Ts.
And in this group of 18 players we had, two of them were players, but they were mostly mechanics.
Recruited for your mechanical ability.
That's good.
So we went to, we started out and I remember going on up to Buffalo and of course it was an experience for me.
And Kendricks was a player and coach and manager, but he was a hard taskmaster.
He had been
coached under Charlie Moran, who had quite a history here at A&M.
He was sort of a disciple of Moran.
And at heart, he was good, but he was strict.
And we really got into, we would practice.
We'd get up, and I want to have two meals a day, and we all stayed in this one big boarding house on Main Street in Buffalo, and we would get up in the morning and eat late breakfast around 10.30.
And then go to the practice field and practice until one-thirty at two and then come back and have our evening meal around four-thirty at five.
And we would go to every place we played.
And in those days they had the New York Giants and the Yankees and the Buffalo, Chicago Bears,
Minnesota, I'm trying to think what they called those, Eskimos, Duluth Eskimos, and Providence, Rhode Island, Pottsville Miners, and those were some of the teams that were in the league.
But it was the National Football League at those times.
The salaries weren't good.
I think most of us players
all of our expenses up there were taken care of.
But that's, you just got paid for a game, not for- For a game, that's right.
And the things I can remember about that game was that league we played all over the East.
And we had a good season.
We finished third in the league, about 15 players.
But the thing I remember about it, the only time we ever went but trained was we played
Now the Philadelphia team was calledit was right out of Philadelphia, but it finally won the team championship.
It was namedwhat was the name of that team?
It was in Philadelphia, but it was a serve over in Philadelphia.
I'll think about it in a minute.
But we played, and this team was coached by Charlie Moran, who had coached Kendricks at A&M.
We played this team in Buffalo on a Saturday and then returned the game in Philadelphia on a Sunday.
And we made the trip, and McKendrick said, now boys, we're going to go by first class.
We're not going to ride any Model T's anymore.
We're going to go by train.
So we had 18 players, I think, counting the two mechanics and everything, going with us.
And we went down to the station.
We were going to leave that night and ride all night.
got on the train, and he said, well, we haven't got the ten tickets for births.
This is all true then.
So he said, now all the guys are going to start regularly.
They're going to have a lower birth, and the guys are going to be substitutes.
They're going to be under the birth.
So that's the way we went down to Philadelphia.
So when the season was over, Jim, he said, well, we'll just play all the way back to Texas, which we did.
He was a great Indian player.
We played his team there twice, once in Oklahoma City and once in Paul Husky.
And then we came on back and played in San Antonio and played down, far down.
Kendricks.
Kendricks, they fired him up there because he, all these cars he brought back, he wasn't crooked or anything.
He just, he thought if anything belonged to him, belonged to you, belonged to him, see.
But anyhow, there was some kind of mix-up in the management of it.
So Kendricks wasn't hired back the next year.
So, Alice and myself got together
Neil Allison, he played here in 24.
So we had a phone call.
You want to hear this?
Yeah, yeah.
Go ahead.
It's fascinating.
Huh?
Go ahead.
You don't want to put it in there?
Yeah, I do.
It's interesting.
I don't think there's anything like this on record.
Go ahead.
So he rang us and said, now listen, I'm going back on up there, and it says that
Why don't you come on up here and go with us?"
So the Buffalo people had sent us our travel expenses.
I think it was $60 in those days.
That's a lot of money.
So Neely Allison was living in Denton, Texas.
We'd been working together all during the summer, and he'd been living in Denton, Texas.
So I went on up to Waco, and Jim was living in Waco.
So when I got there, I said, Jim, the first thing he said was, I said, let's go down to the express office and express your baggage to Buffalo.
I said, I've got the money.
I'm going to ride a truck.
He said, oh, don't throw them on the way on trains.
I said, well, heck, wait.
There's freight trains coming through here today, tonight.
He said, we'll just ride that freight train.
I said, no, I don't.
I said, I got it.
Well, he talked me into it, so I went down there and I expressed my baggage to Buffalo, and so that evening I remember the first time I'd been at A&M, but I hadn't ridden.
I'd been a freight train rider.
So we went out to catch the freight train, and it was going up a big hill, and so we got on there, got on one of these flat cars, I mean, where they carry coal, you know.
meantime he had talked, phoned Neely and he was sort of a pretty religious boy, I mean very clean morally and everything else, but of course he was a football player.
So we got into Fort Worth, we finally got off the train and we got off this train because we had to catch this Sunset, this Texas Special that went through Denton all the way on up
We finally managed to get off the freight train.
You know, in those days, they'd pick you up for riding freight trains.
See, they'd pick you up.
So we finally got off after I stumbled around and fell over some rails.
And so we were riding Neely, and Jim did, and told him that we was coming through on the Texas Special, I think, at a certain, certain time leaving Fort Worth.
So I said, Jim, well, we might as well buy a ticket.
And he said, no, no.
We'd get on the back end of this tender.
So we got on the tender and rode into Denton.
Of course, Neely was down there all dressed up and had all his baggage and everything.
Jim got off and he was all smutty and dirty, you know, cinders and everything.
Of course, he had his mother down there and his girlfriend.
Of course, when he saw Jim, he was horrified.
So Jim came running back before the train was pulling out and said, well, I guess we're going to have to stay all night here.
Neely won't get on the train with us, so I'll make it short.
No, go ahead.
This is a good story.
And so he got off.
We got off and went up and spent the night on the hotel.
And so that morning early, Miss Allison rang in and said,
but this fella Kendrick's can't ride with you boys, and we'll let you have the Ford pickup to go on to providing that Jim gets out of town.
See, she was mad at Jim, see.
So I told Jim, I said, Jim, the best thing for you to do is leave, although you're going with us.
He said, well, okay, I'll be seeing you guys.
So we thought he was going on
hitched another freight train or something along.
The next morning we about, oh it must have been about 10 or 11 o'clock, Neely came by and we went to the hotel and picked us up.
So we started out and got out of town about five miles and there was Kendrick.
So we picked him up.
But the worst, the whole thing about the story, in those days they had a two-seater and then they had a rumble seat.
You call it a rumble seat and you call it a trunk now in the back.
rumble seat all the way to Buffalo.
How long did it take you to drive?
About two and a half, three days.
That's pretty quick.
Yeah.
Jim went on and so he, I don't know whatever happened to him on that particular deal, but the story all entwined.
So we went ahead and played that season, but the middle of the season while we were playing Red Grains team there and it come a terrific snowstorm and the game was canceled.
And so...
It didn't amount to much.
Can you remember how many fans you had at the games?
What kind of crowds?
Oh, we had six, seven thousand, four, five, six thousand people.
Was that a pretty good crowd in those days?
Do you remember what they paid admission?
If I can remember, of course I think it was around a dollar, a dollar and a half, two dollars.
They didn't have much expense.
See, in those days, the headliners made the money like grain.
Brick Muller and those people like that, that were all American, they are the ones that drew the big money.
Just the average.
There weren't many of them.
There weren't many of them.
So we went on after this man went on up and joined the semi-pro team at Harvard, Connecticut and stayed there for four or five games.
And we had a lot of experiences.
And then when Alex and Seth started
St. Mary's University was looking for a football coach.
By chance, they hired Kendricks.
Those were the kind of experiences we had out there.
So you went to work at St. Mary's then?
Assistant football coach.
How long did you stay at St. Mary's?
Well, Jim didn't last but about six months.
Oh, he had a great thing.
He was a great individual.
I mean, he was a personal friend of mine, but he was an adult with a child's mind on some things that he did that were out there.
I could tell you all about it, but anyhow, after the football season was over, they let him go and made me head football coach.
What kind of coach was Kendricks?
He was all right.
He was a good conditioner.
But he was the type of guy that thought he, he wasn't really realistic and sound in his thinking.
And all the football he had learned was under Moran.
And we used to, after the first year he was out there, we used to get those boys up and running a mile every morning for breakfast.
He was a good conditioner, and he had some good points about him.
But he wasn't,
He wasn't realistic and he didn't have good judgment on a lot of things.
Let me drop back a minute and ask you about Bible.
We kind of glanced over him.
Well, I expect DX, I think he was the best all around.
You see, there's different types of coaches.
There's a
loved him and believed in him.
And then there's a type of coach that was just flamboyant, you might say, just didn't have anything.
But Bible was a, he was, see, DX came to A&M as a coach.
He started his coaching career as a player.
Mississippi College.
And then he brought Frank over here when he came here in 1916 or 17.
But D.X.
was a, was my type of coach.
He wasn't a bear, but
gave the rules and regulations, you better not break them.
And then there's the fellow down here that is more or less a fatherly coach that you respected and put out for.
And our Bible was a great coach during that time.
And he was a gentleman coach.
A gentleman coach, that's what I would call him.
A gentleman coach.
Gained your respect easily.
I don't know of anybody that played at A&M that didn't respect and love the X, without a doubt.
Then how long were you head coach now at St. Mary's?
I coached there in 28, 29, 30, and 31.
Do you remember anything about that?
Yes, I had very good luck there.
I coached everything at that time.
Basketball, baseball, and football.
a season by playing DePaul University in Chicago in the Soldiers Field.
And what I remember about that was that Notre Dame, we played on Sunday.
I'm not a Catholic.
We went up there, and the thing I remember about that was Notre Dame and Southern Cal was playing on Saturday at Soldiers Field.
Although I had practiced my team, my wife and some of the brothers and some of the other people who went along with the team saw that game.
I think they had the biggest crowd they ever had, 120,000 people.
And that's when Tremendous in those days.
Yeah.
And that was when Rockne, you know, if you don't remember, but he had been sick.
I know who he was.
We went up on a train and came back on a train.
Did you play at mainly other church schools then?
No, we played Sam Houston Teachers, and we played Texas A&I, and we played St. Edward's, and we played DePaul University, Schreiner Institute, which was a big
most of the state schools, Sol Ross, teams like that.
Well, the second year we had a good team, and the third year the Depression hit us.
And the brothers called me in one day and said, well, I'm sure, I hate to show, but we've got notice from the authorities in St. Louis, see their head school was in,
I don't know what you call them, the school was in St. Louis, and that they had to dispose of football on account of the economy move.
So they had to let you go there?
Well, yeah.
They stopped all sports?
All sports.
And they never did continue on until way back in the late 40s when they started back again.
I see.
Let me stop a minute and turn my tape over.
I'm about to run out on one side.
